WEBVTT

00:01.544 --> 00:03.168
<i> - For two seasons,</i>

00:03.212 --> 00:04.670
<i> America's</i>
<i> most talented bladesmiths</i>

00:04.714 --> 00:06.088
<i> have faced off</i>
<i> in the ultimate competition...</i>

00:06.132 --> 00:07.965
- Getting pretty hot
in the kitchen.

00:08.009 --> 00:10.592
<i> - Making some of history's</i>
<i> deadliest weapons.</i>

00:10.636 --> 00:12.928
<i> Now, with the stakes</i>
<i> higher than ever,</i>

00:12.972 --> 00:14.596
<i> a new batch of bladesmiths</i>
<i> enter the Forge</i>

00:14.640 --> 00:16.223
<i> to test their skills.</i>

00:16.267 --> 00:17.433
- Whoa, whoa,
watch out, watch out, watch out.

00:17.476 --> 00:19.476
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

00:19.520 --> 00:21.687
<i> - Only one will take home</i>
<i> $10,000...</i>

00:21.731 --> 00:23.605
- Whoo!
<i> - And be crowned</i>

00:23.649 --> 00:25.941
<i> "Forged in Fire" champion.</i>

00:25.985 --> 00:28.861
<i> [dramatic music]</i>

00:28.904 --> 00:34.241
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

00:34.285 --> 00:36.160
<i> - I'm Adlai Stein,</i>

00:36.203 --> 00:38.662
<i> and I've been a bladesmith</i>
<i> for 25 years.</i>

00:38.706 --> 00:41.040
Two years ago
I quit my fulltime job

00:41.083 --> 00:43.751
at a law firm
in order to bladesmith.

00:43.794 --> 00:46.795
It's amazing.
I wouldn't go back for anything.

00:46.839 --> 00:50.257
<i> - My name is Raymond Smith.</i>
<i> I'm 69 years old,</i>

00:50.301 --> 00:53.302
and I've been bladesmithing
for probably about 30 years.

00:53.345 --> 00:55.763
<i> I'm a Mastersmith,</i>
<i> and maybe I don't have</i>

00:55.806 --> 00:57.806
the arm and the strength
that I used to have,

00:57.850 --> 01:01.060
but I still have the passion
and the knowledge to go with it.

01:01.103 --> 01:03.896
<i> - My name's Jason Kraus.</i>
<i> My love of bladesmithing</i>

01:03.939 --> 01:07.024
came from sword movies
and all those adventure--

01:07.068 --> 01:09.359
you know, "Lord of the Rings"
and things like that.

01:09.403 --> 01:11.403
<i> Little did I know</i>
<i> I could actually make things</i>

01:11.447 --> 01:13.197
that could perform
like the swords in movies,

01:13.240 --> 01:15.866
you know, for the most part.
[laughs]

01:15.910 --> 01:18.577
<i> - My name is Stephen</i>
<i> Williamson. I'm 19 years old.</i>

01:18.621 --> 01:21.121
I've been smithing
for three years,

01:21.165 --> 01:24.333
and these are
my secret weapons.

01:24.376 --> 01:26.919
- Bladesmiths,
welcome to the Forge.

01:26.962 --> 01:28.378
You know why you're here.

01:28.422 --> 01:29.922
All that stands
between you

01:29.965 --> 01:31.757
and the title
of "Forged in Fire" champion

01:31.801 --> 01:35.260
and that check for $10,000
are three rounds of competition

01:35.304 --> 01:37.679
and, of course,
our three expert judges.

01:37.723 --> 01:39.098
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

01:39.141 --> 01:41.266
Master bladesmith
Jason Knight,

01:41.310 --> 01:42.976
historic weapons
re-creation expert

01:43.020 --> 01:44.978
and swordsmith
David Baker,

01:45.022 --> 01:48.315
kali martial artist
Doug Marcaida.

01:48.359 --> 01:49.817
All right, let's jump
right into this.

01:49.860 --> 01:51.777
On your anvils in front of you
is a cloth.

01:51.821 --> 01:53.362
Go ahead
and lift that up.

01:53.405 --> 01:55.197
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

01:55.241 --> 01:58.242
That is a massive chunk
of steel,

01:58.285 --> 01:59.868
more than enough steel
to make a knife.

01:59.912 --> 02:01.120
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

02:01.163 --> 02:03.330
Here's the catch.

02:03.374 --> 02:05.415
Today you won't be
making knives.

02:05.459 --> 02:07.292
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

02:07.336 --> 02:10.087
Your first round challenge
is to forge a hatchet

02:10.131 --> 02:13.090
with an integral handle
in your signature style.

02:13.134 --> 02:14.716
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

02:14.760 --> 02:17.511
- Wow, that sucks.

02:17.555 --> 02:18.679
- Is anybody nervous?

02:18.722 --> 02:20.722
- Very.
- Terrified.

02:20.766 --> 02:23.684
I've never made
anything like this.

02:23.727 --> 02:25.310
<i> - Even though I have to make</i>
<i> a hatchet,</i>

02:25.354 --> 02:27.813
I think I can make it
through this thing.

02:27.857 --> 02:31.650
It's basically
a funky-shaped knife.

02:31.694 --> 02:33.068
- Keep in mind
that in round two

02:33.112 --> 02:35.028
you'll be attaching
handle material

02:35.072 --> 02:37.489
to your hatchets to turn them
into fully functional weapons.

02:37.533 --> 02:40.325
It will then be tested
in a rope slice...

02:40.369 --> 02:43.120
and a log chop.

02:43.164 --> 02:45.455
The blades themselves must fall
within the following parameters.

02:45.499 --> 02:47.207
The length of the cutting edge
of your hatchet

02:47.251 --> 02:50.002
<i> must be at least 4 inches.</i>

02:50.045 --> 02:51.461
<i> The total length</i>
<i> of your weapon</i>

02:51.505 --> 02:53.505
<i> from the top</i>
<i> of the hatchet head</i>

02:53.549 --> 02:56.592
<i> to the bottom of the tang</i>
<i> must not exceed 22 inches</i>

02:56.635 --> 02:59.511
<i>and must be at least 15 inches.</i>

02:59.555 --> 03:01.221
You have ten minutes
to work on your design.

03:01.265 --> 03:03.724
You'll have three hours
to forge your blades.

03:03.767 --> 03:05.893
We've never had
a hatchet challenge

03:05.936 --> 03:06.894
in the first round,
gentlemen.

03:06.937 --> 03:09.479
This is gonna be huge.

03:09.523 --> 03:11.982
Good luck.
Your time starts...

03:12.026 --> 03:12.983
now.

03:13.027 --> 03:17.237
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

03:17.281 --> 03:18.655
- All right.

03:18.699 --> 03:20.115
- These guys right now
have to come up

03:20.159 --> 03:22.075
with a signature hatchet.

03:22.119 --> 03:23.619
- Jason's signature hatchet
probably has

03:23.662 --> 03:25.913
a distinguished beard.

03:25.956 --> 03:27.497
- Turn that side, please.
There you go.

03:27.541 --> 03:30.167
- Like this.
[both laughing]

03:30.211 --> 03:32.836
<i> - It's gonna be interesting</i>
<i> working with other smiths.</i>

03:32.880 --> 03:34.838
One of the best things
that I like about bladesmithing

03:34.882 --> 03:38.967
<i> is you're working alone</i>
<i> 99% of the time.</i>

03:39.011 --> 03:41.970
<i> The hatchet that I'm making</i>
<i> is a woodsman's type hatchet,</i>

03:42.014 --> 03:45.265
<i> 85% function and 15% looks.</i>

03:45.309 --> 03:46.600
It's not made to sit
on the mantel.

03:46.644 --> 03:49.102
It's a working tool.

03:49.146 --> 03:52.731
<i> - I have no drawing skill,</i>
<i> so I'm doodling giant hatchets</i>

03:52.775 --> 03:54.608
<i> until I can figure out</i>

03:54.652 --> 03:57.736
what I really need to do
when I get with the forge.

03:57.780 --> 04:00.530
<i> I'm Jewish, so my heritage</i>
<i> is very important to me</i>

04:00.574 --> 04:03.825
and being a Jewish bladesmith,
and that's what defines me.

04:03.869 --> 04:05.327
I'm going to crush
the competition

04:05.371 --> 04:06.328
with my Hebrew hammer.

04:06.372 --> 04:08.330
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

04:08.374 --> 04:11.667
- A hatchet is a small axe
that is meant to be light

04:11.710 --> 04:13.252
<i> and to be carried</i>
<i> long distances</i>

04:13.295 --> 04:16.171
and used for multiple tasks.

04:16.215 --> 04:17.422
- We told them
we didn't want a axe.

04:17.466 --> 04:19.341
We want a hatchet,

04:19.385 --> 04:22.678
and a hatchet has to be able
to be used with one hand.

04:22.721 --> 04:24.721
- One hand.

04:24.765 --> 04:27.516
<i> - I'd say the most experience</i>
<i> I have making anything</i>

04:27.559 --> 04:31.436
of this sort would be a cleaver
that you use in a kitchen,

04:31.480 --> 04:34.523
<i> so I'm going to design</i>
<i> this thing</i>

04:34.566 --> 04:39.361
to be a giant, weird-looking
cleaver hatchet.

04:39.405 --> 04:41.530
That's what I've got to go on.

04:41.573 --> 04:42.781
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

04:42.825 --> 04:45.284
- I'm making a basic hatchet

04:45.327 --> 04:48.036
that has
a really dropped handle,

04:48.080 --> 04:50.455
<i> make it easier for chopping.</i>

04:50.499 --> 04:52.332
<i> I'm different</i>
<i> from the average 19-year-old</i>

04:52.376 --> 04:55.627
<i> because I'm going after</i>
<i>a whole different set of goals.</i>

04:55.671 --> 04:58.297
<i> I would like to be</i>
<i> a professional bodybuilder.</i>

04:58.340 --> 05:00.799
<i> I would like to be</i>
<i> a master bladesmith.</i>

05:00.843 --> 05:03.468
Bladesmithing and bodybuilding
are a lot alike

05:03.512 --> 05:06.513
in the fact that
you have to focus

05:06.557 --> 05:09.808
and, um--

05:09.852 --> 05:10.767
<i> [dramatic drum hit]</i>

05:10.811 --> 05:12.269
[clicks tongue]

05:12.313 --> 05:13.979
Oh, [bleep].

05:14.023 --> 05:16.606
- Bladesmiths, your
design period is now closed.

05:16.650 --> 05:19.776
Your three-hour forge time
starts...

05:19.820 --> 05:21.695
now.

05:21.739 --> 05:23.405
Here we go.
- All right.

05:23.449 --> 05:25.073
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

05:25.117 --> 05:28.577
- This is easily
three times larger

05:28.620 --> 05:30.579
than any piece of stock steel

05:30.622 --> 05:32.789
we've ever given
our bladesmiths.

05:32.833 --> 05:36.877
There's a lot of metal
to manipulate in this challenge.

05:36.920 --> 05:39.629
- They actually probably have
enough to do normal-size one

05:39.673 --> 05:42.424
and then a miniature one.
[laughs]

05:42.468 --> 05:44.885
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

05:44.928 --> 05:46.928
- It's taking forever
to heat up.

05:46.972 --> 05:51.767
This 8-by-4-inch chunk of steel,
that's a lot of metal to move.

05:51.810 --> 05:53.435
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

05:53.479 --> 05:56.396
Not entirely sure
I can do it in three hours.

05:56.440 --> 05:58.523
<i> My mind is reeling</i>
<i> with possibilities</i>

05:58.567 --> 06:00.859
of how to move
that metal around

06:00.903 --> 06:04.279
and what the end product
may or may not look like.

06:04.323 --> 06:06.114
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

06:06.158 --> 06:09.159
- How do they manipulate
this steel?

06:09.203 --> 06:11.536
What is the first thing
that they have to do?

06:11.580 --> 06:14.081
- The first thing that
they should be doing is

06:14.124 --> 06:16.875
isolating the head
and handle area.

06:16.919 --> 06:19.669
Once that's isolated,
I would draw the handle out.

06:19.713 --> 06:22.422
Next I would start
working on the head.

06:22.466 --> 06:23.799
<i> - I'm pretty confident</i>
<i> with making</i>

06:23.842 --> 06:25.092
<i> a hatchet like this.</i>

06:25.135 --> 06:26.468
I've seen it done
a couple times.

06:26.512 --> 06:28.053
I've never done it myself.

06:28.097 --> 06:29.971
I think it's gonna
pan out pretty good.

06:30.015 --> 06:31.348
<i> - I'm not really confident.</i>

06:31.392 --> 06:33.767
I have never made
a hatchet before,

06:33.811 --> 06:36.561
<i> but Ray seems</i>
<i> pretty stinking chill,</i>

06:36.605 --> 06:38.522
and that is freaking me out.

06:38.565 --> 06:41.024
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

06:41.068 --> 06:44.986
- Ray already cut 2 inches
off of his handle.

06:45.030 --> 06:46.988
- Yeah, they don't have to use
all the material.

06:47.032 --> 06:48.824
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

06:48.867 --> 06:51.451
- Wow, look at the size
of the steel

06:51.495 --> 06:54.162
coming out of Jason's forge.

06:54.206 --> 06:56.706
- We've given the smiths
so much metal

06:56.750 --> 06:59.751
that they have to really
exercise a sense of scale.

06:59.795 --> 07:02.170
- A hatchet has to be
light and fast.

07:02.214 --> 07:04.506
The lighter you can make it,
the better.

07:04.550 --> 07:05.882
- Again, we didn't tell them
they had to use

07:05.926 --> 07:07.509
the whole piece of steel,

07:07.553 --> 07:11.346
so it's a part of the challenge,
which I like.

07:11.390 --> 07:13.098
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

07:13.142 --> 07:15.142
- I think competing
with a Mastersmith

07:15.185 --> 07:17.102
<i> is something</i>
<i> that I did not expect.</i>

07:17.146 --> 07:19.354
I am honored, thrilled,

07:19.398 --> 07:23.400
and terrified
that it's going to...

07:23.444 --> 07:25.444
be my doom.
[laughs]

07:25.487 --> 07:27.362
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

07:27.406 --> 07:29.072
- Ray actually looks
kind of bored.

07:29.116 --> 07:30.615
[laughter]

07:30.659 --> 07:32.742
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

07:32.786 --> 07:34.744
<i> - I'm making</i>
<i> pretty good headway so far.</i>

07:34.788 --> 07:36.329
I've never made a hatchet before
in three hours,

07:36.373 --> 07:37.998
but I'm gonna give it
a shot today.

07:38.041 --> 07:39.458
- Stephen doesn't need
a power hammer.

07:39.501 --> 07:40.792
- No.
- He's the power hammer.

07:40.836 --> 07:43.753
- He is the power hammer.
[laughter]

07:43.797 --> 07:47.841
- I'm shaping the handle first
because I like to use

07:47.885 --> 07:49.426
<i> the handle of whatever</i>
<i> I'm working on.</i>

07:49.470 --> 07:51.178
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

07:51.221 --> 07:52.929
I don't like using tongs
too much.

07:52.973 --> 07:54.723
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

07:54.766 --> 07:57.350
<i> I'm kind of going</i>
<i> with the kukri style</i>

07:57.394 --> 07:59.478
<i>'cause it's meant for chopping.</i>

07:59.521 --> 08:02.814
Whenever a handle is curved,
it puts the cutting edge

08:02.858 --> 08:04.691
<i> a little lower</i>
<i> than your hand</i>

08:04.735 --> 08:06.943
so you don't have to extend
your wrist all the way down

08:06.987 --> 08:09.154
whenever you're chopping things.

08:09.198 --> 08:11.364
- Yeah, the way his handle's
going is out of control.

08:11.408 --> 08:13.408
- It's actually putting
the knuckles

08:13.452 --> 08:15.202
in line with the edge.

08:15.245 --> 08:16.745
- Is that a good idea, or--
- That's a bad one.

08:16.788 --> 08:18.747
- No, that's a bad idea.
- Yeah.

08:18.790 --> 08:20.749
- The curve in the handle
should be subtle.

08:20.792 --> 08:22.292
Too much curve will
cause that thing

08:22.336 --> 08:23.877
to want to twist
back and forth

08:23.921 --> 08:25.128
when you're trying
to cut with it.

08:25.172 --> 08:28.757
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

08:28.800 --> 08:31.009
- One hour has elapsed!

08:31.053 --> 08:34.679
You have two hours remaining
to finish your work!

08:34.723 --> 08:36.640
- What'd you say?

08:36.683 --> 08:43.855
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

08:43.899 --> 08:46.358
- I'm not focusing
the way I need to be.

08:46.401 --> 08:47.609
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

08:47.653 --> 08:50.278
<i> I'm feeling drained.</i>

08:50.322 --> 08:52.489
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

08:52.533 --> 08:54.074
- Uh-oh.
- That'll happen.

08:54.117 --> 08:55.784
I hope he's doing all right.

08:55.827 --> 08:58.995
<i>- I'm having trouble breathing.</i>

08:59.039 --> 09:01.623
God, don't let me fall over and
hit my head on this concrete.

09:01.667 --> 09:03.124
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

09:03.168 --> 09:05.043
<i> I kind of rest on the anvil</i>

09:05.087 --> 09:07.671
<i> until somebody asks me</i>
<i> if I'm okay,</i>

09:07.714 --> 09:09.798
and I kind of realize
that I'm not.

09:09.841 --> 09:11.508
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

09:11.552 --> 09:14.636
- So Adlai's stepping out
of the Forge.

09:14.680 --> 09:17.347
This is definitely a concern.

09:17.391 --> 09:19.432
Time does not stop.

09:19.476 --> 09:21.268
- I try to catch my breath.

09:21.311 --> 09:23.770
I drink more water...

09:23.814 --> 09:25.647
and just try to breathe,

09:25.691 --> 09:27.065
<i> and it's getting</i>
<i> more and more difficult.</i>

09:27.109 --> 09:28.066
Holy crap.

09:28.110 --> 09:31.820
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

09:35.450 --> 09:38.994
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

09:39.037 --> 09:40.704
- We got a smith down.

09:40.747 --> 09:44.207
Adlai, he's been outside
for nearly 20 minutes.

09:44.251 --> 09:47.752
Until you're here,
until you experience the heat

09:47.796 --> 09:49.671
and the pressure of competition,

09:49.715 --> 09:52.382
you cannot possibly fathom

09:52.426 --> 09:55.802
what these guys go through
physically and mentally.

09:55.846 --> 09:58.054
We've never had a smith
step away

09:58.098 --> 10:00.473
from the Forge floor
for this long.

10:00.517 --> 10:04.811
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

10:04.855 --> 10:08.315
- I'm finally getting this thing
drawn out to an edge.

10:08.358 --> 10:11.568
<i> I think that the design that</i>
<i> I made will look pretty stupid</i>

10:11.612 --> 10:15.655
if I don't accentuate the fact
that the kind of hatchet

10:15.699 --> 10:17.907
<i> I'm making has</i>
<i> a cleaver twist to it.</i>

10:17.951 --> 10:20.660
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

10:20.704 --> 10:23.622
- Jason, he has actually
used a drift

10:23.665 --> 10:27.584
to put a hole through
his axe head

10:27.628 --> 10:29.002
in the same way
that you would see,

10:29.046 --> 10:30.670
like, a cartoon cleaver.

10:30.714 --> 10:33.006
- Here's the discussion.
Is that a hatchet?

10:33.050 --> 10:38.678
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

10:38.722 --> 10:40.180
- Let's do it.
I want to finish this.

10:40.223 --> 10:41.306
- He's driving out
the bottom so--

10:41.350 --> 10:42.432
- All right.
- All right.

10:42.476 --> 10:45.268
[applause]

10:45.312 --> 10:47.062
- He's back.

10:47.105 --> 10:49.064
- I don't want to go back
to a desk job.

10:49.107 --> 10:51.775
I want to prove to myself that
this is what I'm meant to do.

10:51.818 --> 10:54.653
- Over 20 minutes Adlai
had to step off the Forge floor.

10:54.696 --> 10:56.488
That's what it took
for him to recover.

10:56.531 --> 10:59.324
<i> - The best I could do is</i>
<i> to go back in</i>

10:59.368 --> 11:02.285
with the time I've got left
and just keep going.

11:02.329 --> 11:04.120
There's no quit.

11:04.164 --> 11:05.872
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

11:05.916 --> 11:09.959
- Ray's head compared to Adlai
and Jason and Stephen,

11:10.003 --> 11:12.837
instead of being,
like, a huge flyswatter,

11:12.881 --> 11:17.133
he's brought it down
to, like, the width of an axe.

11:17.177 --> 11:19.302
- With a hatchet like this
you have to draw it out,

11:19.346 --> 11:21.471
and when you draw it out
under the power hammer,

11:21.515 --> 11:23.306
<i> you end up with your handle</i>
<i> in the center</i>

11:23.350 --> 11:26.393
<i> of the hatchet head,</i>
<i> so you have to offset that,</i>

11:26.436 --> 11:28.603
or you're gonna have
a real funny-looking hatchet.

11:28.647 --> 11:31.731
- Mostly forging
is technique.

11:31.775 --> 11:35.110
Use the right techniques and
metal will flow just like clay.

11:35.153 --> 11:36.528
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

11:36.571 --> 11:38.905
- You've got Ray,
who has 30 years

11:38.949 --> 11:41.032
of blade-making experience.

11:41.076 --> 11:43.535
Two anvils away,
you have Stephen,

11:43.578 --> 11:46.204
who has three years.

11:46.248 --> 11:48.206
<i> - I'm 19.</i>
<i> I've only had three years,</i>

